The "AI vs Human Text" dataset on Kaggle is designed to aid in distinguishing between text generated by artificial intelligence and text authored by humans. The dataset includes multiple examples of both AI-generated and human-written texts, annotated accordingly. This collection can be invaluable for research into AI detection methods and for educational purposes, such as helping teachers identify whether students might be using AI to complete assignments. The dataset supports efforts in developing tools or conducting studies related to text authenticity and origin verification. In this dataset AI is labeled as 1 and Human is labeled as 0.

# Load Glove (use this same code just change the file name for Concept Net)
def load_embeddings(filename):
    """
    Load a DataFrame from the generalized text format used by word2vec, GloVe,
    fastText, and ConceptNet Numberbatch. The main point where they differ is
    whether there is an initial line with the dimensions of the matrix.
    """
    labels = []
    rows = []
    with open(filename, encoding='utf-8') as infile:
        for i, line in enumerate(infile):
            items = line.rstrip().split(' ')
            if len(items) == 2:
                # This is a header row giving the shape of the matrix
                continue
            labels.append(items[0])
            values = np.array([float(x) for x in items[1:]], 'f')
            rows.append(values)
    
    arr = np.vstack(rows)
    return pd.DataFrame(arr, index=labels, dtype='f')

embeddings = load_embeddings('../glove.6B.300d.txt')

Discuss methods of tokenization in your dataset as well as any decisions to force a specific length of sequence:

The method of tokenization we used tokenizes the input data by converting words into integer indices based on their frquency in the text. This method also provides flexibility in terms of selecting the number of top words to consider. We chose to use the longest sequence length of 1400 shown in the graph as the maximum number of words because we do not want any of the sentences to be cut off.

The metric we will use to evaluate our algorithms performance is the f1-score. The F1-score will be used as the threshold/confidence level because in the context of using this algorithm to determine if a student used AI to complete their homework or not we dont want to prioritize one result or the other by falsely assuming a kid used AI to complete their homework or not catching a student that has used AI to complete their homework. False positives for both sides are equally important in this context so the F1 score is best evaluation metric.

X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.2, stratify=y)

We decided to split the data in an 80/20 split. 20% of the data will be used for testing and 80% will be used for training. Setting stratify=y ensures that the class distribution in the dataset is preserved in both the training and testing sets. By randomly spliting the data into training and testing sets while preserving class proportions, we create a realistic simulation of how a model is used in the real world.

# 300 because that is the size of Glove
EMBED_SIZE = 300

def create_embeddings_matrix(embeddings):
    # now fill in the matrix, using the ordering from the
    #  keras word tokenizer from before
    found_words = 0
    embedding_matrix = np.zeros((len(word_index) + 1, EMBED_SIZE))
    for word, i in word_index.items():
        try:
            embedding_vector = np.array(embeddings.loc[[word]])
        except:
            continue
        # words not found in embedding index will be ALL-ZEROS
        embedding_matrix[i] = embedding_vector
        found_words = found_words+1

    print("Embedding Shape:",embedding_matrix.shape, "\n",
        "Total words found:",found_words, "\n",
        "Percentage:",100*found_words/embedding_matrix.shape[0])
    
    return embedding_matrix

embedding_matrix = create_embeddings_matrix(embeddings)

# the input is a list of integers, 500 long
sequence_input = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))

# this will reduce the input dimension from VOCAB_SIZE to 50 for each word
# the lenght will be the maximum number of words in a document, so 500
embedded_sequences = embedding_layer(sequence_input)

# starting sequence size is 500 (words) by 50 (embedded features)
x = Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(embedded_sequences)

# after conv, length becomes: 500-4=496 
# so overall size is 496 by 64

# now pool across time
x = MaxPooling1D(5)(x)# after max pool, 496/5 -> 99 by 64
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

# extract additional features
x = Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

# new size is 95 after the conovlutions
x = MaxPooling1D(5)(x) # after max pool, size is 95/5 = 19 by 64
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

# more features through CNN processing!
x = Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

# after convolution, size becomes 15 elements long
# Take the mean of these elements across features, result is 64 elements
x_mean = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x) # this is the size to globally flatten 

# Take the variance of these elements across features, result is 64 elements
x_tmp = Subtract()([x,x_mean])
x_std = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x_tmp**2)

x = Concatenate(name='concat_1')([x_mean,x_std])

x = Dense(64, activation='relu',
          kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

preds = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid',
              kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform')(x)

model1 = Model(sequence_input, preds)

print(model1.summary())

plot_model(
    model1, to_file='model1.png', show_shapes=True, show_layer_names=True,
    rankdir='LR', expand_nested=False, dpi=96
)

Transformers:¶

In [ ]:
from tensorflow.keras.layers import MultiHeadAttention, LayerNormalization
from tensorflow.keras import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Layer

# The transformer architecture 
class TransformerBlock(Layer): # inherit from Keras Layer
    def __init__(self, embed_dim, num_heads, ff_dim, rate=0.2):
        super().__init__()
        # setup the model heads and feedforward network
        self.att = MultiHeadAttention(num_heads=num_heads, 
                                      key_dim=embed_dim)
        
        # make a two layer network that processes the attention
        self.ffn = Sequential()
        self.ffn.add( Dense(ff_dim, activation='relu') )
        self.ffn.add( Dense(embed_dim) )
        
        self.layernorm1 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)
        self.layernorm2 = LayerNormalization(epsilon=1e-6)
        self.dropout1 = Dropout(rate)
        self.dropout2 = Dropout(rate)

    def call(self, inputs, training = False):
        # apply the layers as needed (similar to PyTorch)
        
        # get the attention output from multi heads
        # Using same inpout here is self-attention
        # call inputs are (query, value, key) 
        # if only two inputs given, value and key are assumed the same
        attn_output = self.att(inputs, inputs)
        
        # create residual output, with attention
        out1 = self.layernorm1(inputs + attn_output)
        
        # apply dropout if training
        out1 = self.dropout1(out1, training=training)
        
        # place through feed forward after layer norm
        ffn_output = self.ffn(out1)
        out2 = self.layernorm2(out1 + ffn_output)
        
        # apply dropout if training
        out2 = self.dropout2(out2, training=training)
        #return the residual from Dense layer
        return out2
    
class GloveTokenAndPositionEmbedding(Layer):
    def __init__(self):
        super().__init__()
        # create two embeddings 
        # one for processing the tokens, pretrained (words)
        self.token_emb = Embedding(
            len(word_index) + 1,
            EMBED_SIZE,
            embeddings_initializer=Constant(embedding_matrix),# here is the embedding getting saved
            input_length=MAX_ART_LEN,
            trainable=False
        )
        
        # another embedding for processing the position
        self.pos_emb = Embedding(MAX_ART_LEN, 
                                 EMBED_SIZE, 
                                 input_length=MAX_ART_LEN,
                                 trainable=True
                                )

    def call(self, x):
        # create a static position measure (input)
        maxlen = tf.shape(x)[-1]
        positions = tf.range(start=0, limit=maxlen, delta=1)
        # positions now goes from 0 to 500 (for IMdB) by 1
        positions = self.pos_emb(positions)# embed these positions
        x = self.token_emb(x) # embed the tokens
        return x + positions # add embeddngs to get final embedding

def mcnemar(y, yhat1, yhat2):
    b = 0
    c = 0
    
    for i in range(len(y)):
        if yhat1[i] == yhat2[i]:
            continue
        if yhat1[i] == y[i]:
            b +=1
        else:
            c +=1
            
    m = ((np.abs(b-c) -1) ** 2)/(b+c) 
    print(m)
    # critical value for 95% confidence
    return m > 3.841

# heatmap to compare the performance of of 5 models
from sklearn import metrics as mt
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns
%matplotlib inline

def heatmaps(y, yhats, labels=["Human", "AI"]):
    plt.figure(figsize=(30,5))
    for i, yhat in enumerate(yhats):
        acc_cnn = mt.accuracy_score(y_test,yhat)
        plt.subplot(1,len(yhats),i+1)
        cm = mt.confusion_matrix(y,yhat)
        cm = cm/np.sum(cm,axis=1)[:,np.newaxis]
        print(cm)
        sns.heatmap(cm, annot=True, fmt='.2f')
        plt.title(f'Model {i+1}: {acc_cnn:.4f}')
        
    plt.show()

Model 6¶

For Model 6 we used the better performer of our two CNN models. Since both CNNs, Model 1 and 2 had the same F1-scores and McNemar did not show signifcant differences we chose the better of the two based on which model was faster. the faster model of the two was Model 2. So for Model 6 we use the model from Model 2 and train it using ConceptNet instead of Glove.

In [ ]:
# the input is a list of integers, 500 long
sequence_input = Input(shape=(X_train.shape[1], ))

# this will reduce the input dimension from VOCAB_SIZE to 50 for each word
# the lenght will be the maximum number of words in a document, so 500
embedded_sequences = embedding_layer(sequence_input)

# starting sequence size is 500 (words) by 50 (embedded features)
x = Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(embedded_sequences)

# after conv, length becomes: 500-4=496 
# so overall size is 496 by 64

# now pool across time
x = MaxPooling1D(5)(x)# after max pool, 496/5 -> 99 by 64
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

# more features through CNN processing!
x = Conv1D(64, 5, activation='relu',
           kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)
x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

# after convolution, size becomes 15 elements long
# Take the mean of these elements across features, result is 64 elements
x_mean = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x) # this is the size to globally flatten 

# Take the variance of these elements across features, result is 64 elements
x_tmp = Subtract()([x,x_mean])
x_std = GlobalAveragePooling1D()(x_tmp**2)

x = Concatenate(name='concat_1')([x_mean,x_std])

x = Dense(64, activation='relu',
          kernel_initializer='he_uniform')(x)

x = Dropout(0.2)(x)

preds = Dense(1, activation='sigmoid',
              kernel_initializer='glorot_uniform')(x)

model6 = Model(sequence_input, preds)

print(model6.summary())

For Model 2 vs Model 6, the Mcnemar test returned a degree of dissagreement of 0.13 which suggests a significant difference between these two models in terms of their predictive performance. This value, 0.13 is less than the critical value of a 95% confidence level, which is 3.84. This means there is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis that there is no difference between the two models based on this test. Therefore, according to McNemar's test, there is not a significant difference between Model 2 and Model 6 in terms of their predicitons on our data. Model 2's F1_scores are 0: 0.98 and 1: 0.97. And Model 6's F1_scores are 0: 0.98 and 1: 0.97. So, based on our evaluation criteria Model 2 and Model 6 performed the same. This leaves use to use run time as the determining factor. To run 5 Epochs, Model 2 took 0.8 seconds fewer than Model 6. So in conclusion, Model 2 slightly outperformed Model 6.
